This book dives so deep into the experience of being a bystander and living with complicity.

I love that you said most of us are Sue Snells rather than Carrie Whites. 

I spend so much time thinking about the stories we tell ourselves as queer people ‚Äî or even just the stories we tell ourselves about being an outsider. 

I think we all have different contexts in which we have been a Sue Snell, a Carrie White, or hell, even a Chris. 

But it is so much easier to focus on the times we have been tormented or bullied. When we‚Äôve been Carrie.

Even if we have far more often been a Sue or a Chris.

It seems like remakes of this story make it much more about Carrie ‚Äî even as a villain, there is sympathy for her as she rises up against her tormenters.

I feel like that type of story is very popular in 2022. 

But the book demands you sit with the times you‚Äôve been a Sue. When you‚Äôve been complicit. 

And it also explores WHY we choose to be complicit. 

